# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frederick-winslow-taylor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-u-s-national-championships-doubles] The doubles champions of the first U.S. championships were Clarence Clark and Frederick Winslow Taylor.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-u-s-national-championships-doubles] It seems to have consisted of four rounds.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-u-s-national-championships-doubles] In the first round, Clark and Taylor defeated Smith and Crawford Nightingale.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-u-s-national-championships-doubles] In a second match, Alexander Van Rensselaer and Arthur Newbold (*né* Arthur Emlen Newbold; 1859–1920) beat Arthur Rives and Stevens 6–5 and 6–2.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-u-s-national-championships-doubles] Like in the singles competition, except for the final, each match was played on the best of three sets.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-us-national-championships-tennis] National Championship** (now known as the US Open) was a tennis tournament that took place in August 1881 at the Newport Casino, Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-us-national-championships-tennis] For the first and only time, only clubs that were members of the United States National Lawn Tennis Association were permitted to enter the tournament.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-us-national-championships-tennis] A Men's Singles competition and a Men's Doubles competition were played, and Richard Sears became the first men's singles U.S.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1881-us-national-championships-tennis] (United States) Richard Sears defeated (United Kingdom) William E.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1882-u-s-national-championships-doubles] Sears and Dwight defeated Nightingale and Smith in the final of the second U.S. doubles championship.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1884-u-s-national-championships-doubles] James Dwight and Richard Sears defended their title against Alexander Van Rensselaer and Walter Berry in the final.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1886-u-s-national-championships-doubles] Sears and Dwight won the doubles title by beating Taylor and Brinley in four sets in the final.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1886-u-s-national-championships-doubles] The final was played on August 26, 1886.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1888-u-s-national-championships-men-s-doubles] Valentine Hall and Oliver Campbell won their first doubles title at the U.S. championships.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was born in 1856 to a Quaker family in Germantown, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor's father, Franklin Taylor, a Princeton-educated lawyer, built his wealth on mortgages.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor's mother, Emily Annette Taylor (née Winslow), was an ardent abolitionist and a coworker with Lucretia Mott.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His father's ancestor, Samuel Taylor, settled in Burlington, New Jersey, in 1677.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His mother's ancestor, Edward Winslow, was one of the fifteen original Mayflower Pilgrims who brought servants or children, and one of eight who had the honorable distinction of Mister.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Winslow served for many years as the Governor of the Plymouth colony.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The Taylor family had inherited wealth and property, and the family's assets were maintained by Franklin's older brother, Caleb Newbold Taylor.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Educated early by his mother, Taylor studied for two years in France and Germany and traveled Europe for 18 months.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1872, he entered Phillips Exeter Academy in Exeter, New Hampshire, with the plan of eventually going to Harvard University and becoming a lawyer like his father.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1874, Taylor passed the Harvard entrance examinations with honors.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] However, due allegedly to rapidly deteriorating eyesight caused by night study, Taylor chose quite a different path.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Instead of attending Harvard University, Taylor became an apprentice patternmaker and machinist, gaining shop-floor experience at Enterprise Hydraulic Works in Philadelphia (a pump-manufacturing company whose proprietors were friends of the Taylor family).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] During this time, his eyesight recovered.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He left his apprenticeship for six months and represented a group of New England machine-tool manufacturers at Philadelphia's centennial exposition.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor finished his four-year apprenticeship and in 1878 became a machine-shop laborer at Midvale Steel Works.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] At Midvale, he was quickly promoted to time clerk, journeyman machinist, machine shop foreman, research director, and finally chief engineer of the works (while maintaining his position as machine shop foreman).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor's fast promotions reflected both his talent and his family's relationship with Edward Clark, part owner of Midvale Steel.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Early on at Midvale, working as a laborer and machinist, Taylor recognized that workmen were working their machines, or themselves, not nearly as hard as they could (a practice that at the time was called "soldiering") and that this resulted in high labor costs for the company.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] When he became a foreman he expected more output from the workmen.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In order to determine how much work should properly be expected, he began to study and analyze the productivity of both the men and the machines (although the word "productivity" was not used at the time, and the applied science of productivity had not yet been developed).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His focus on the human component of production Taylor labeled scientific management.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] While Taylor worked at Midvale, he and Clarence Clark won the first tennis doubles tournament in the 1881 US National Championships, the precursor of the US Open.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor became a student of Stevens Institute of Technology, studying via correspondence and obtaining a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering in 1883.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] From 1890 until 1893 Taylor worked as a general manager and a consulting engineer to management for the Manufacturing Investment Company of Philadelphia, a company that operated large paper mills in Maine and Wisconsin.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1893, Taylor opened an independent consulting practice in Philadelphia.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His business card read "Consulting Engineer - Systematizing Shop Management and Manufacturing Costs a Specialty".
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Through these consulting experiences, Taylor perfected his management system.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His first paper, *A Piece Rate System*, was presented to the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) in June 1895.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1898 he joined Bethlehem Steel to solve an expensive machine-shop capacity problem.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The inventors received US$100,000 (equivalent to about $3,900,000 in 2025) for the English patents alone, although the U.S. patent was eventually nullified.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was forced to leave Bethlehem Steel in 1901 after discord with other managers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Now a wealthy man, Taylor focused the remainder of his career promoting his management and machining methods through lecturing, writing, and consulting.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] From 1904 - 1914, Taylor lived in Philadelphia with his wife and three adopted children.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1910, owing to the Eastern Rate Case, Frederick Winslow Taylor and his Scientific Management methodologies became famous worldwide.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1911, Taylor introduced his The Principles of Scientific Management paper to the ASME, eight years after his Shop Management paper.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] On October 19, 1906, Taylor was awarded an honorary degree of Doctor of Science by the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In the same year, he was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1912.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] That same year, he gave testimony to a special committee of the US House of Representatives regarding his own and other systems of management.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor eventually became a professor at the Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth College.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In early spring of that year, Taylor caught pneumonia and died, one day after his fifty-ninth birthday, on March 21, 1915.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He was buried in West Laurel Hill Cemetery, in Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was a mechanical engineer who sought to improve industrial efficiency.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He is regarded as the father of scientific management, and was one of the first management consultants and director of a famous firm.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Scientifically select, train, and develop each employee rather than passively leaving them to train themselves.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Divide work nearly equally between managers and workers, so that the managers apply scientific management principles to planning the work and the workers actually perform the tasks.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Future US Supreme Court justice Louis Brandeis coined the term *scientific management* in the course of his argument for the Eastern Rate Case (Brandeis vs Eastern Railroad) before the Interstate Commerce Commission in 1910.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Brandeis argued that railroads, when governed according to Taylor's principles, did not need to raise rates to increase wages.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor used Brandeis's term in the title of his monograph *The Principles of Scientific Management,* published in 1911.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The Eastern Rate Case propelled Taylor's ideas to the forefront of the management agenda.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor wrote to Brandeis, "I have rarely seen a new movement started with such great momentum as you have given this one." Taylor's approach is also often referred to as *Taylor's Principles*, or, frequently disparagingly, as *Taylorism*.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Workers were to be selected appropriately for each task.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor believed in transferring control from workers to management.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He set out to increase the distinction between mental (planning work) and manual labor (executing work).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Detailed plans, specifying the job and how it was to be done, were to be formulated by management and communicated to the workers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The introduction of his system was often resented by workers and provoked numerous strikes.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The strike at Watertown Arsenal led to the congressional investigation in 1912.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor believed the laborer was worthy of his hire, and pay was linked to productivity.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His workers were able to earn substantially more than those under conventional management, and this earned him enemies among the owners of factories where scientific management was not in use.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor promised to reconcile labor and capital.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Debate about Taylor's Bethlehem study of workers, particularly the stereotypical laborer "Schmidt", continues to this day.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] One 2009 study supports assertions Taylor made about the quite substantial increase in productivity, for even the most basic task of picking up, carrying and dropping pigs of iron.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor thought that by analyzing work, the "one best way" to do it would be found.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He is most remembered for developing the stopwatch time study, which, combined with Frank Gilbreth's motion study methods, later became the field of time and motion study.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He broke a job into its component parts and measured each to the hundredth of a minute.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] One of his most famous studies involved shovels.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He noticed that workers used the same shovel for all materials.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He determined that the most effective load was 21½ pounds, and found or designed shovels that for each material would scoop up that amount.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He was generally unsuccessful in getting his concepts applied, and was dismissed from Bethlehem Iron Company/Bethlehem Steel Company.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Nevertheless, Taylor was able to convince workers who used shovels and whose compensation was tied to how much they produced to adopt his advice about the optimum way to shovel by breaking the movements down into their component elements and recommending better ways to perform these movements.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] It was largely through his disciples' efforts (most notably Henry Gantt's) that industry came to implement his ideas.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Moreover, the book he wrote after parting company with the Bethlehem company, *Shop Management*, sold well.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor's written works were designed for presentation to the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] These include *Notes on Belting* (1894), *A Piece-Rate System* (1895), *Shop Management* (1903), *Art of Cutting Metals* (1906), and *The Principles of Scientific Management* (1911).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was president of the ASME from 1906 to 1907.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] While president, he tried to implement his system into the management of the ASME but met with much resistance.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He was able to reorganize only the publications department and that only partially.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He also forced out the ASME's longtime secretary, Morris Llewellyn Cooke, and replaced him with Calvin W.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] His tenure as president was trouble-ridden and marked the beginning of a period of internal dissension within the ASME during the Progressive Age.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1911, Taylor collected a number of his articles into a book-length manuscript, which he submitted to the ASME for publication.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The ASME formed an ad hoc committee to review the text.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The committee included Taylor allies such as James Mapes Dodge and Henry R.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The committee delegated the report to the editor of the *American Machinist*, Leon P.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Alford was a critic of the Taylor system and his report was negative.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The committee modified the report slightly, but accepted Alford's recommendation not to publish Taylor's book.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor angrily withdrew the book and published *Principles* himself in 1912, without ASME approval.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In France, Le Chatelier translated Taylor's work and introduced scientific management throughout government owned plants during World War I.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] This influenced the French theorist Henri Fayol, whose 1916 *Administration Industrielle et Générale* emphasized organizational structure in management.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] " He suggests that Taylor has staff analysts and advisors working with individuals at lower levels of the organization to identify the ways to improve efficiency.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Around 1922 the journalist Paulette Bernège became interested in Taylor's theories, which were popular in France in the post-war period.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Bernège became the faithful disciple of the Domestic Sciences Movement that Christine Frederick had launched earlier in the United States, which Bernège adapted to French homes.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Frederick had transferred the concepts of Taylorism from the factory to domestic work.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] These included suitable tools, rational study of movements and timing of tasks.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Scientific standards for housework were derived from scientific standards for workshops, intended to streamline the work of a housewife.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The *Comité national de l'organisation française* (CNOF) was founded in 1925 by a group of journalists and consulting engineers who saw Taylorism as a way to expand their client base.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Founders included prominent engineers such as Henry Louis Le Châtelier and Léon Guillet.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Bernège's Institute of Housekeeping Organization participated in various congresses on the scientific organization of work that led up to the founding of the CNOF, and in 1929 led to a section in CNOF on domestic economy.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Older historical accounts used to suggest that British industry had less interest in Taylor's teachings than in similarly sized countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] More recent research has revealed that British engineers and managers were as interested as in other countries.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Particularly enthusiastic were the Cadbury family, Seebohm Rowntree, Oliver Sheldon and Lyndall Urwick.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In addition to establishing a consultancy to implement Taylor's system, Urwick, Orr & Partners, Urwick was also a key historian of F.W.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor and scientific management, publishing *The Making of Scientific Management* trilogy in the 1940s and *The Golden Book of Management* in 1956.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In Switzerland, the American Edward Albert Filene established the International Management Institute to spread information about management techniques.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Lyndall Urwick was its director until the IMI closed in 1933.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In the Soviet Union, Vladimir Lenin was very impressed by Taylorism, which he and other Bolshevik leaders tried to incorporate into Soviet manufacturing.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] When Joseph Stalin took power in the 1920s, he championed the theory of "Socialism in one country" which denied that the Soviet economy needed foreign help to develop, and open advocates of Western management techniques fell into disfavor.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] No longer celebrated by Soviet leadership, Taylorism and the mass production methods of Henry Ford remained silent influences during the industrialization of the Soviet Union.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor and his theories are also referenced (and put to practice) in the 1921 dystopian novel *We* by Yevgeny Zamyatin.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In the early 1920s, the Canadian textile industry was re-organized according to scientific management principles.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1928, workers at Canada Cotton Ltd. in Hamilton, Ontario went on strike against newly introduced Taylorist work methods.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Also, Henry Gantt, who was a close associate of Taylor, re-organized the Canadian Pacific Railway.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] With the prevalence of US branch plants in Canada and close economic and cultural ties between the two countries, the sharing of business practices, including Taylorism, has been common.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The Taylor Society was founded in 1912 by Taylor's allies to promote his values and influence.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] A decade after Taylor's death in 1915 the Taylor Society had 800 members, including many leading U.S. industrialists and managers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In 1936 the Society merged with the Society of Industrial Engineers, forming the Society for Advancement of Management, which still exists today.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Many of the critiques of Taylor come from Marxists.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] The earliest was by Antonio Gramsci, an Italian Communist, in his *Prison Notebooks* (1937).
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Gramsci argued that Taylorism subordinates the workers to management.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He also argued that the repetitive work produced by Taylorism might actually give rise to revolutionary thoughts in workers' minds.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Harry Braverman's work *Labor and Monopoly Capital: The Degradation of Work in the Twentieth Century*, published in 1974, was critical of scientific management and of Taylor in particular.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] This work pioneered the field of Labor Process Theory as well as contributing to the historiography of the workplace.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Management theorist Henry Mintzberg is highly critical of Taylor's methods.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Mintzberg states that an obsession with efficiency allows measurable benefits to overshadow less quantifiable social benefits completely, and social values get left behind.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor's methods have also been challenged by socialists.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Their arguments relate to progressive defanging of workers in the workplace and the subsequent degradation of work as management, powered by capital, uses Taylor's methods to render work repeatable and precise yet monotonous and skill-reducing.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Rinehart argued that Taylor's methods of transferring control over production from workers to management, and the division of labor into simple tasks, intensified the alienation of workers that had begun with the factory system of production around the period 1870 to 1890.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Frederick Taylor has been criticized by his approach to management, which focused on maximizing efficiency and productivity by breaking down tasks to simplest components often resulted in the dehumanization of workers.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] Taylor was an accomplished tennis and golf player.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] He and Clarence Clark won the inaugural United States National tennis doubles championship at Newport Casino in 1881, defeating Alexander Van Rensselaer and Arthur Newbold (*né* Arthur Emlen Newbold; 1859–1920) in straight sets.
[src:frederick-winslow-taylor/frederick-winslow-taylor] In the 1900 Summer Olympics, Taylor finished fourth in golf.
